WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.640
Hi everyone, this is Yihui Xie.

00:00:08.640 --> 00:00:14.720
Sorry that I can't attend the RStudio conference in person this year, but I guess you won't

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:17.719
miss anything from this talk with my absence.

00:00:17.719 --> 00:00:24.959
Well, if you really miss my face, you can simply google for my picture and stare at

00:00:24.959 --> 00:00:28.920
it for 20 minutes along with this talk.

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:38.400
So there are people who are really familiar with my previous talks and work on the so-called

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:39.400
down packages.

00:00:39.400 --> 00:00:45.520
They are so familiar that every time they meet me, they don't greet me with the usual

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:46.520
what's up.

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:48.520
Instead, they say, what's down?

00:00:48.520 --> 00:00:52.720
Well, this time I'm not going to talk about any down packages.

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:56.160
I won't let you down as usual.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:57.799
So what's down?

00:00:57.799 --> 00:00:58.799
Nothing is down.

00:00:58.799 --> 00:00:59.799
What's up?

00:00:59.799 --> 00:01:01.320
Quarto is up.

00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:07.760
So most down packages have had or will have equivalents in Quarto, which you might have

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:12.400
heard for several times at this conference.

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:19.400
And I need to, I probably should clarify that the down packages won't be down anytime soon.

00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:21.400
We will continue to maintain them.

00:01:21.400 --> 00:01:25.800
So why am I talking about Knitr today?

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:31.919
Because the Knitr package is a common cornerstone of Quarto and RMarkdown.

00:01:31.919 --> 00:01:34.720
So both of them are built on top of Knitr.

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:40.279
So you can apply what you have learned today about Knitr in this talk to both Quarto and

00:01:40.279 --> 00:01:41.879
RMarkdown documents.

00:01:41.879 --> 00:01:46.599
So Knitr has existed for a little over 10 years.

00:01:46.599 --> 00:01:51.040
So the development started in 2011.

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:55.599
And I made the first crane release in January, 2012.

00:01:55.599 --> 00:02:00.320
Over these years, I have made more than 50 crane releases.

00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:07.720
And there have been more than 5,000 questions on Stack Overflow and more than 2,000 GitHub

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:09.960
issues and pull requests.

00:02:09.960 --> 00:02:17.479
I would also like to thank all the Knitr contributors, and there are more than 100 of them.

00:02:17.479 --> 00:02:22.600
Since the pandemic, I have almost lost track of time.

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:28.679
So basically, I want to look back and see what I have done in the past two years, whether

00:02:28.679 --> 00:02:31.279
I have done anything meaningful.

00:02:31.279 --> 00:02:34.880
So as I said, Knitr is over 10 years old.

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:42.600
So it has become quite mature and probably inevitably boring as time goes by.

00:02:42.679 --> 00:02:50.559
When things become mature, they often become boring too, just like adults, kids are much

00:02:50.559 --> 00:02:51.559
more fun.

00:02:51.559 --> 00:02:57.720
Yeah, for software, being mature is not bad, it's actually a good thing.

00:02:57.720 --> 00:03:05.320
In this talk, I'm not going to talk about any totally exciting new features because

00:03:05.320 --> 00:03:12.039
there are not any huge new features in recent years in the development of Knitr.

00:03:12.479 --> 00:03:15.360
But I would like to highlight a few little things.

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:21.520
So for a full list of changes and new features, you can check out the release notes of Knitr

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:22.520
later.

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:28.440
So the first thing I want to highlight is that now you have a new way to write chunk

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:29.440
options.

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:35.839
Previously, you must write all chunk options on one line in the chunk header.

00:03:35.839 --> 00:03:42.119
Now you can write them on multiple lines as special comments in the beginning of the

00:03:42.119 --> 00:03:43.720
chunk body.

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:50.279
So this special comment starts with the hash character followed by the pipe character.

00:03:50.279 --> 00:03:56.039
I'm not sure how would you pronounce this combination.

00:03:56.039 --> 00:03:57.039
Maybe hashpipe?

00:03:57.039 --> 00:04:05.639
I remember someone mentioned to me that hashpipe was a funny coincidence.

00:04:05.639 --> 00:04:10.279
Since I'm not a native English speaker, I had no idea what hashpipe means.

00:04:10.279 --> 00:04:13.360
So I googled for that and I regret it.

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:18.880
Anyway, hashpipe comments, you can use that to write chunk options.

00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:24.519
So as I said previously, you have to force all the chunk options onto a single line,

00:04:24.519 --> 00:04:27.559
which is sometimes very awkward.

00:04:27.559 --> 00:04:35.799
If you have many, many chunk options for a single chunk, there will be an awkward horizontal

00:04:35.799 --> 00:04:36.799
scroll bar.

00:04:36.799 --> 00:04:43.500
But now you can write all of your chunk options can write with your chunk body.

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:48.440
You can put them inside the chunk after the special comments.

00:04:48.440 --> 00:04:53.019
And you can also hard wrap all these lines freely.

00:04:53.019 --> 00:04:57.519
You can write them on any number of lines.

00:04:57.519 --> 00:05:05.000
For example, you can put one chunk option on one line, or you can break a single chunk

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:06.000
option in the middle.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.799
You can wrap them in any way you like.

00:05:08.799 --> 00:05:16.359
And alternatively, you can also use the YAML syntax to provide your chunk options.

00:05:16.359 --> 00:05:23.519
So previously I'm showing the old syntax of comma separated chunk options of the form

00:05:23.519 --> 00:05:27.399
option equals value and separated by commas.

00:05:27.399 --> 00:05:34.279
If you're familiar with YAML, you know that syntax will be option colon followed by value.

00:05:34.279 --> 00:05:38.160
And you have to write one option per line.

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:45.000
For Quartel and RStudio or VS Code users, I strongly recommend that you use the YAML

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:53.320
syntax because the editors, RStudio and VS Code, they have better support for the YAML

00:05:53.320 --> 00:05:54.320
options.

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:59.119
For example, they can help you outcomplete the option names.

00:05:59.119 --> 00:06:03.559
They can validate the values of your options.

00:06:03.559 --> 00:06:11.299
And second, the YAML syntax works for other engines in Quartel as well, such as Jupyter.

00:06:11.299 --> 00:06:18.000
So if you want to convert the old syntax to the new syntax, there is a function named

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:21.000
convertChunkHeader in Niter.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:27.839
So you can use that function to convert your old R Markdown documents to using the new

00:06:27.839 --> 00:06:30.239
syntax for chunk options.

00:06:30.239 --> 00:06:33.320
This requires a very recent version of Niter.

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:42.200
And the second thing I want to talk about is how to reuse both chunk options and chunk

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:45.799
content from other code chunks.

00:06:45.839 --> 00:06:52.359
Previously, there existed several ways to reuse the content of a code chunk.

00:06:52.359 --> 00:06:57.480
For example, through the ref.label option.

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:04.519
So suppose you have one code chunk with the label chunk A, and then you can write another

00:07:04.519 --> 00:07:12.440
code chunk with the label chunk B, but set the chunk option ref.label equals chunk A.

00:07:12.519 --> 00:07:22.200
ref.label equals chunk A, that means I want to copy the chunk content of chunk A into

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:30.079
chunk B. So now, although you see the chunk B is empty here, but when you execute this

00:07:30.079 --> 00:07:37.839
document, chunk B will have the same content as chunk A. You can learn more about reusing

00:07:37.839 --> 00:07:41.000
the chunk content in the R Markdown cookbook.

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:49.480
So now, in addition to reusing the content of code chunks, you can also reuse chunk options

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:52.200
from other code chunks.

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:57.239
And this can be done through the chunk option ops.label.

00:07:57.239 --> 00:08:01.920
So for example, you have chunk A here, and you have set a couple of chunk options on

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:10.959
chunk A. And if you want to use the same chunk options in chunk B, then you simply can set

00:08:10.959 --> 00:08:17.679
ops.label equals chunk A. So instead of repeating all the chunk options from chunk A, you simply

00:08:17.679 --> 00:08:24.320
set a single option, ops.label equals chunk A. And then chunk B will use the same chunk

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:26.399
options as chunk A.

00:08:26.399 --> 00:08:34.080
Then, if you want to reuse both chunk options and the content from other code chunks, you

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:44.840
can set the chunk option ref.label to the label of other code chunks, and then wrap

00:08:44.840 --> 00:08:51.280
the labels in the function I. For example, here I have chunk A, which has a few chunk

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:55.880
options, and then it also has some chunk content.

00:08:55.880 --> 00:09:02.679
And then in chunk B, I set ref.label equals I chunk A. That means I want to use both the

00:09:02.679 --> 00:09:08.359
content of chunk A and the chunk options of chunk A. So in that way, you don't have

00:09:08.359 --> 00:09:15.440
to repeat everything from chunk A. You simply set a single option, and Niter will copy everything

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:19.599
to chunk B.

00:09:19.599 --> 00:09:23.000
So I also want to share two quick tips.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:31.900
First, the chunk options ref.label and ops.label can take a vector of chunk labels.

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:37.340
That means you can reuse multiple code chunks instead of a single one.

00:09:37.340 --> 00:09:44.140
Second, you can provide further local chunk options.

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:51.380
If a code chunk has some local chunk options, they will override the reused options of the

00:09:51.380 --> 00:09:52.940
same names.

00:09:52.940 --> 00:10:00.700
So in this example, chunk B is basically reusing both chunk options and the chunk content of

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:08.820
chunk A, but it has set a local chunk option dev equals png.

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:15.619
So since we have borrowed all the chunk options from chunk A, which includes the chunk option

00:10:15.619 --> 00:10:17.900
dev equals svg.

00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:25.260
So now chunk B, since chunk B has a local chunk option dev equals png, this dev equals

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:31.380
png will override the dev equals svg from chunk A.

00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:39.580
So basically, local chunk options will have higher priorities if you reuse chunk options

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:42.179
from other code chunks.

00:10:42.179 --> 00:10:48.219
Third thing I want to mention is the new chunk options in Niter in recent years.

00:10:48.219 --> 00:10:55.780
We have added a few of them, but today I'm just going to mention one of them here, which

00:10:55.780 --> 00:10:57.979
is the file option.

00:10:57.979 --> 00:11:06.739
So sometimes you may want to develop code in an external script and include it in code

00:11:06.739 --> 00:11:07.739
chunk.

00:11:07.739 --> 00:11:13.219
Previously, what you could do is to use the chunk option code.

00:11:13.219 --> 00:11:21.780
So for example, here I'm using the chunk option code that takes the value from readlines.script.r.

00:11:21.780 --> 00:11:26.940
So that basically means I want to read an external script and pass the content of that

00:11:26.940 --> 00:11:32.700
script to the code option, and then Niter knows, okay, I will use the content of that

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:37.340
script as the content of this code chunk.

00:11:37.340 --> 00:11:44.179
That's the previous way of including external scripts into a code chunk.

00:11:44.179 --> 00:11:50.700
Now this can be simplified to the chunk option file.

00:11:50.700 --> 00:11:55.140
So you can set file equals a file path, for example, script.r.

00:11:55.140 --> 00:12:02.619
So basically that's equivalent to using code equals readlines.script.r before.

00:12:02.619 --> 00:12:06.859
And this file option also supports a vector of file paths.

00:12:06.859 --> 00:12:13.979
For example, you can pass two scripts to the file option and the file option will read

00:12:13.979 --> 00:12:18.299
both of them into the code chunk.

00:12:18.299 --> 00:12:25.059
The fourth thing I want to highlight is some new engines in Niter.

00:12:25.059 --> 00:12:26.780
The first one is the comment engine.

00:12:27.340 --> 00:12:32.539
You can use the comment engine to comment out any content.

00:12:32.539 --> 00:12:41.340
And the content can contain basically anything, including code chunks or inline R expressions

00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:43.940
or other paragraphs or anything.

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:48.440
So basically there's one rule that you have to remember.

00:12:48.440 --> 00:12:56.359
If the comment contains like three backticks, and then for the comment engine, you have

00:12:56.359 --> 00:12:58.679
to start with four backticks.

00:12:58.679 --> 00:13:05.400
So basically the rule is that if your comment contains N backticks, then the comment engine

00:13:05.400 --> 00:13:08.640
needs to start with N plus one backticks.

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:15.159
So if the content is commented out, it will not be included in the output.

00:13:15.640 --> 00:13:21.280
The second engine is the verbatim engine, and this can be very useful when you want

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:27.359
to write tutorials on R Markdown.

00:13:27.359 --> 00:13:32.760
You may want to display some content verbatim, especially the code chunks.

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:39.080
When you want to display a code chunk verbatim, you can use the verbatim engine.

00:13:39.080 --> 00:13:40.640
And the rule is the same.

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:46.400
So for example, here I'm including a code chunk with three backticks, and then the verbatim

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:50.280
engine needs to start with four backticks.

00:13:50.280 --> 00:14:00.719
For the verbatim engine, depending on the language of the content, you can set a syntax

00:14:00.719 --> 00:14:05.200
highlighting language through the chunk option lang.

00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:08.119
So for example, here I'm using lang equals Markdown.

00:14:08.119 --> 00:14:19.159
That means the verbatim content here is Markdown code, but this lang option is optional.

00:14:19.159 --> 00:14:26.840
So it depends on whether you want syntax highlighting in your output for the verbatim content.

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:37.200
Previously, I have introduced some old ugly hacks on how to show content verbatim, and

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:40.599
now you can forget all of them.

00:14:40.599 --> 00:14:45.320
And here, I just, yeah, I don't want to explain this anymore.

00:14:45.320 --> 00:14:47.719
This is just too ugly.

00:14:47.719 --> 00:14:53.679
Use the verbatim engine and forget about the old ugly hacks.

00:14:53.679 --> 00:14:59.760
The third engine that I want to show is the embed engine.

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:07.159
You can use the embed engine to embed external files, text files actually.

00:15:07.159 --> 00:15:11.840
You can embed external text files and display their content verbatim.

00:15:11.840 --> 00:15:21.479
So this is similar to the verbatim engine, but you can use the file option to embed external

00:15:21.479 --> 00:15:22.640
files.

00:15:22.640 --> 00:15:27.080
So you don't have to write the content in the chunk body.

00:15:27.080 --> 00:15:31.159
You just point the file option to some file paths.

00:15:31.159 --> 00:15:37.119
And alternatively, you can write file paths in the chunk body of the embed engine.

00:15:37.119 --> 00:15:43.039
For example, you can write quote foo.r, quote bar.r.

00:15:43.039 --> 00:15:47.840
So the second way has a tiny advantage.

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:54.400
That is, if you write in the chunk body, if you write the file paths in the chunk body,

00:15:54.400 --> 00:16:00.599
your editor, for example, RStudio, may be able to out-complete the file paths.

00:16:00.599 --> 00:16:06.940
The last engine that I want to show here is the exec engine.

00:16:06.940 --> 00:16:15.440
So this engine allows you to execute an arbitrary system command on a file that contains the

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:17.760
content of the chunk.

00:16:17.760 --> 00:16:23.719
So that command can be specified through the chunk option command.

00:16:23.799 --> 00:16:32.919
For example, I have an exec engine here, and I'm using the command equals bash.

00:16:32.919 --> 00:16:42.280
That means I want to run the command bash on the command that I specified in the chunk

00:16:42.280 --> 00:16:43.599
body.

00:16:43.599 --> 00:16:52.679
So basically, when Nitrus sees an exec chunk, it will write the chunk body into a file and

00:16:52.679 --> 00:16:56.700
execute a command on that file.

00:16:56.700 --> 00:17:01.960
So for this bash example, actually, you don't have to use the exec engine.

00:17:01.960 --> 00:17:05.680
You can simply use the existing bash engine in Nitrus.

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:11.040
So these two code chunks are pretty much equivalent.

00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:17.800
There have existed a lot of command-based engines in Nitrus, for example, awk, or go,

00:17:17.800 --> 00:17:20.359
or perl, or zshell.

00:17:20.479 --> 00:17:26.760
From now on, we no longer need to add a new engine for every single command.

00:17:26.760 --> 00:17:32.319
You can basically use the exec engine to execute any command.

00:17:32.319 --> 00:17:37.520
And by the way, the exec engine is also extensible.

00:17:37.520 --> 00:17:45.719
If you're interested, you can go back and check out the example through the link here.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:55.400
For those who are curious about how the exec engine works, basically, Nitrus will execute

00:17:55.400 --> 00:18:10.239
a command of the form command args1 args2, where args is a file path, and this file contains

00:18:10.239 --> 00:18:13.239
the content of the code chunk.

00:18:13.239 --> 00:18:19.359
And args1 and args2 are optional command-line arguments that you may specify through the

00:18:19.359 --> 00:18:21.920
chunk option engine.ops.

00:18:21.920 --> 00:18:31.839
So here I have an example that executes the grep command with a few command-line arguments

00:18:31.839 --> 00:18:36.160
dash i, which means case-insensitive matching.

00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:39.719
And then the pattern is he.

00:18:39.719 --> 00:18:44.880
And I want to execute grep on the four lines of text here.

00:18:44.880 --> 00:18:51.920
So, you know, he will, if you match he in case-insensitivity, it will match the first

00:18:51.920 --> 00:19:00.359
line, hellos, and the third line, since it has the, which contains he.

00:19:00.359 --> 00:19:06.439
And just a quick recap, we have talked about four things in today's talk.

00:19:06.439 --> 00:19:10.199
First thing is that you can use hashpipe comments in the chunk body to write chunk

00:19:10.199 --> 00:19:11.199
options.

00:19:11.199 --> 00:19:18.560
Then you can use ops.label and ref.label options to reuse both chunk options and content.

00:19:18.560 --> 00:19:24.920
And third, you can use the file option to read external files as the chunk content.

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:31.280
And last, we have introduced a few new engines in Nitru.

00:19:31.280 --> 00:19:33.000
That's all I have for you today.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.599
Thank you very much, and happy knitting!

